[[H. Rider Haggard]], [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]] ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|h|æ|g|ər|d}}; 1856 – 1925) was an English writer, largely of [[adventure fiction]], but also of non-fiction. The eighth child of a [[Norfolk]] barrister and squire,<ref name="Times: Obit" /> through family connections he gained employment with [[Henry Bulwer, 1st Baron Dalling and Bulwer|Sir Henry Bulwer]] during the latter's service as lieutenant-governor of [[Colony of Natal|Natal]], South Africa.{{sfn|Cohen|2004}} Rider Haggard travelled to southern Africa in 1875 and remained in the country for six years, during which time he served as Master of the High Court of the [[Transvaal Colony|Transvaal]] and an adjutant of the [[Pretoria Horse]].<ref name="Times: Obit" />

Rider Haggard's time in Africa proved inspirational for him,<ref name="Gage CA" /> and while still in Natal he wrote two articles for ''[[The Gentleman's Magazine]]'' describing his experiences.{{sfn|McKay|1930|p=81}} He returned to Britain in 1881 and was [[called to the bar]]; while studying he wrote his first book, ''[[Cetywayo and His White Neighbours]]'', a critical examination of Britain's policies in South Africa.{{sfn|Cohen|2004}} Two years later he published his first work of fiction, ''[[Dawn (Rider Haggard novel)|Dawn]]''. In 1885 he wrote one of his most popular novels, ''[[King Solomon's Mines]]''—detailing the life of the adventurer [[Allan Quatermain]]—which was followed by ''[[She: A History of Adventure]]'' (1886), which introduced the female character Ayesha, both of which became series of books;{{efn|Ayesha was a beautiful sorceress who had discovered the secret of eternal life. She is described by ''The Oxford Encyclopedia of British Literature'' as being "a femme fatale", who is "an unattainable and yet eternally faithful lover, at once ravishing, dangerous, magical, all-powerful".{{sfn|Brantlinger|2006|p=496}}}} according to the author [[Morton N. Cohen]], writing for the ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', much of Rider Haggard's reputation rests on these two works.{{sfn|Cohen|2004}} Although he mostly concentrated on his non-fiction and his novels, he also produced a number of short-stories, which have been released in three collections.<ref name="Gage CA" />

Rider Haggard was interested in land affairs and wrote several works on the subject; in 1895 he served on a government commission to examine [[The Salvation Army|Salvation Army]] labour colonies, and in 1911 he served on the [[Royal Commission]] examining coastal erosion. He was an inveterate letter writer to ''[[The Times]]'', and had nearly 100 letters published by the newspaper.<ref name="Times: Obit" />{{sfn|Cohen|2004}}

