{{Other uses|Potlatch (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox software | name = Potlatch | logo = Potlatch 2 Logo.png | logo size = 250px | screenshot = potlatch2.png | screenshot size = 250px | caption = Potlatch 2 with OpenStreetMap data | developer = Richard Fairhurst | released = | latest release version = 2.4<ref>https://github.com/systemed/potlatch2/releases</ref> | latest release date = {{Start date|2015|7|4}} | programming language = [[ActionScript]] | platform = [[Adobe Flash]] | status = Active | language count = 94<ref>https://github.com/systemed/potlatch2/tree/master/l10n/locale</ref> | genre = [[GIS software]] | license = [[WTFPL]]<ref>{{cite web|title=OpenStreetMap Potlatch 2 git repository|url=http://git.openstreetmap.org/potlatch2.git/|accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref> }}
'''Potlatch''' is a [[free software]] editing tool for [[OpenStreetMap]] [[geodata]] using [[Adobe Flash]]. It is one of two editors embedded directly within the OpenStreetMap website.
Potlatch&nbsp;2 requires a [[web browser]] with at least version&nbsp;8 of the Flash plugin installed. It continues to be actively maintained.
== History == Potlatch&nbsp;1<ref>{{cite web|title=P1 repository|url=https://trac.openstreetmap.org/browser/subversion/applications/editors/potlatch}}</ref> was released mid 2006<ref>{{cite web|title=Potlatch 1|first=Richard|last=Fairhurst|url=http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/w/index.php?title=Potlatch_1&oldid=7072}}</ref> and was the default editor on the main OpenStreetMap site until it was replaced by Potlatch&nbsp;2 in April 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Awesone Patlatch 2 team awarded Lolcat of Awesomeness|first=Richard|last=Weait|url=https://blog.openstreetmap.org/2011/04/07/awesome-potlatch-2-team-awarded-lolcat-of-awe/}}</ref> The name ''Potlatch'' came from the name of newsletter of the [[Lettrist International]] art collective.<ref name="starts-editor"/>
An [[alpha version]] of Potlatch&nbsp;2, a complete reimplementation of the software, was published in summer 2010. In December 2010, Potlatch&nbsp;2 was released for general use. After [[Microsoft]] had granted OpenStreetMap permission to use aerial imagery from their [[Bing Maps]] service for tracing, Potlatch 2 was extended to display these images in the background.
[[iD (software)|iD]] (current default editor on main OpenStreetMap website) is in turn a reimplementation of Potlatch&nbsp;2 architecture in [[JavaScript]].<ref name="starts-editor">{{cite web|title=It all starts with an editor|last=Fairhurst|first=Richard|url=http://www.systemed.net/blog/index.php?post=24|accessdate=2012-11-02|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023145335/http://www.systemed.net/blog/index.php?post=24|archivedate=2012-10-23|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=MacWright|first=Tom|title=iD Updates|url=http://mapbox.com/osmdev/2012/11/14/id-updates/|publisher=MapBox|accessdate=20 November 2012}}</ref>
